\title{Extending roxygen2: a custom \verb{@spell} tag}
\description{
roxygen2 isn't limited to its built-in tags. You can define your own by
writing a few S3 methods, as described in
\code{vignette("extending", package = "roxygen2")} (also at
\url{https://roxygen2.r-lib.org/articles/extending.html}). \verb{@spell} below is a
fun example: a Harry Potter themed version of the \verb{@tip} tag, rendered as a
"Try this spell" section marked with a magic wand (🪄), so it stands out
from the rest of the help page. Styled as an HTML callout.
}
\details{
The three methods involved:
\itemize{
\item \code{roxy_tag_parse()} decides how the raw tag text is parsed. Here we hand
it to \code{\link[roxygen2:tag_parsers]{roxygen2::tag_markdown()}} so \verb{@spell} supports the same Markdown
(\code{code}, \emph{emphasis}, links) as everything else.
\item \code{roxy_tag_rd()} turns the parsed tag into an \code{\link[roxygen2:rd_section]{roxygen2::rd_section()}},
which is how roxygen2 collects and merges tags of the same kind across
a block.
\item \code{format.rd_section_spell()} turns that section into actual \code{.Rd}
syntax, i.e. the text roxygen2 writes into the \verb{man/*.Rd} file. For the
HTML rendering it converts the tag's Markdown to HTML itself (via the
\code{commonmark} package, already a roxygen2 dependency).
}

Because these methods extend generics that live in roxygen2 (not in this
package), each is exported with \verb{@exportS3Method pkg::generic} rather
than a plain \verb{@export}. See \code{vignette("namespace")}. And because
\code{roxygen2::roxygenise()} loads this package before it scans it for
documentation, the tag is available to use on functions defined right
here (see \code{R/spells.R}) with no extra wiring. Reuse it from another
package and you would additionally need
\code{Config/roxygen2/packages: helppages} in that package's \code{DESCRIPTION},
as explained in the vignette linked above.
